But not in chronological order, jumping between time periods as she spends time under government experimentation, as a rising star in the CIA and on the run from the law. The temporal disorder makes sense in theory; the trajectory of Jodie’s life means that events unfolding concurrently would lead to a pacing issue. However, in practice the narrative jumps around so violently and frequently between time periods that the story struggles to gain a foothold. It lacks a singular narrative thread to tie the scenes together, leading to a disparate collection of vignettes. Top secret government labs, CIA training montages, teenage parties, homelessness, snowball fights, makeshift midwifery (with the most staggeringly unrealistic depiction of birth I’ve ever seen), spiritual war in the Navajo desert, civil war in Somalia.
